This is a very common behavioral question. The hiring manager wants to see:

Do you accept mistakes

Do you take responsibility

Do you learn from them

Never say “I never made a mistake.”
Instead show learning and improvement.

Use this structure:

Situation → Mistake → Fix → Learning

Example Answer (Good for a Developer)

In one of my previous projects, I was working on a feature that involved updating some database records through an API. While implementing it, I missed handling a particular edge case where a null value could be passed in the request.

This caused an issue in the staging environment during testing. Once the issue was identified, I quickly analyzed the logs, reproduced the problem locally, and fixed the validation logic. I also added additional test cases to ensure the scenario was properly covered.

That experience taught me the importance of considering edge cases and writing more comprehensive validations and tests when implementing APIs.

Another Good Example (Code Review Scenario)

Early in my career, I implemented a feature where my database queries were not optimized, which caused an N+1 query problem. During code review, a senior developer pointed it out and explained how it could impact performance when the dataset grows.

I refactored the code using eager loading to fix the issue and learned more about query optimization in Rails. Since then, I’ve been more careful about analyzing database queries and performance when implementing features.

Why These Answers Work

They show:

✅ Responsibility
✅ Problem-solving
✅ Learning mindset

Managers like candidates who learn from mistakes.

💡 Small interview trick:
Say a mistake that is not critical to your ability.

Good mistakes:

Missing edge cases

Performance issue

Learning from code review

Avoid mistakes like:

Deleting production data

Breaking production repeatedly

Missing deadlines frequently

